as this is a rolling average with the fulough scheme in place for a couple months now, May unemployment is likely to be lower increase than April. 2m drawing benefit in April implies c6%. i think to get above 7% requires a huge increase in May.

UK unemployment seems to be calculated in a 3 month moving average. March was 3.9%. It is well reported April was up 69%, which would be 6.59% for April. May is projected to be 8-10%, which would put the three month average between the 6-7% range. May would have to be above 10.45% for the average to go above 7%, which I find unlikely because it makes more sense for most of the unemployment claims to be in the first month of the lockdown. The lockdown started the last week of March. In the US initial jobless claims peaked the second week of the lockdown and dropped every week after that. So it is unlikely the UK May jump will be more than the UK April jump. I am giving the above 7% category a little extra credit because I don't want to underestimate the impact of the virus and because I thought we were heading into a global recession before the virus even hit.
A day to go and I'll go all in.

It's also important to read section 3 about how anyone who works at least one hour or is expecting to return to a job (includes furloughed workers) do not count as unemployed:
If the following assumptions are true, then there will probably be an unemployment rate of ~6.0% [1]:

Based on my initial take on the relation between unemployment numbers and unemplyoment rate, the unemplyoment rate should be well above 7.0% [1]. Currently, there are more than 3.3 million people officially registered as unemployed meaning they are also not covered by the furlough scheme [2,3,4]. Assuming we have ~34 million as the base of people able to work, then we would only need to have ~2.38 million unemployed people to get above 7.0%. In reference to official statistics, Berenberg indicates that the unemployment rate was ~3.9% in March, ~6.0% in April and expects it to be ~9.5% for May [4].

The UK unemployment rate in the 3 months leading up to February 2020 was already estimated at a record high. The rate was 4% in the 3 months to Feb 2020. Given the COVID-19 impact on employment, despite the furlough scheme, there are still significant numbers who have lost employment due to companies insolvency and those working in sectors where wages are not a significant portion of the company costs.

In normal times we see little seasonal variation in unemployment rates between Nov to Jan and Jan to March. So can assume a base rate of around 4%. Unemployed people are defined as those aged 16 or over who are without work, available to start work in the next two weeks and who have either: a) been actively seeking work in the past four weeks, or. b) are waiting to start a new job they have already obtained.

The surge in new claims wipe out 77% of the 1.23 million new jobs created between the referendum of June 2016 and January 2020 while implying a severe increase in unemployment that's likely to lift the jobless rate by 2.7 percentage points to 6.6% for the three months to the end of March.

First of all it is important to note that the widely reported surge in Universal Credit claims [1] does not necessarily correlate exactly with unemployment as ONS use a Labour Force survey as a measurement and the claimant count is usually *below* the unemployment rate [2]. The 950K surge implies at least an unemployment rate of approx 6.3%, however this is likely to be underestimating the actual unemployment rate - though not necessarily by much (the difference between claimant count and unemployment was about 0.1% in the last dataset). I am also sceptical of the forecasts made by financial institutions who seemed to underestimate the size of the crisis incoming judging by their economic forecasts from March 2020 [3]. I am aware this data will have been compiled quite a bit earlier than publication date but it should have been clear by the start of March the scale of the crisis. I expect current lockdown will continue for the duration of this question and given the economic package announced I don't expect another surge like we've seen with the initial spike. I think the crowd is underestimating the chance of a 6-7% unemployment rate as data suggests that is the current level however I accept there is the capacity for this figure to grow - even if not as much as the initial spike and this would take it over to the 7% figure. Given the post GFE baserate of unemployment being over 7% in the UK is quite high and adjusting for this extraordinary scenario I make 7% or over the most likely outcome but between 6-7% also being feasible.

The outlook is relatively grim for the UK’s economy as the virus continues to spread. Several firms estimate a 6% unemployment rate for the next period, but there is a high chance this could be a low-ball. Sunak’s proposal for furloughing workers, whose salaries can be paid at 80% on the government dime, will no doubt be helpful, but much of the damage has been done already, in a slow-burn fashion that may not yet be readily apparent. Johnson’s delay in taking drastic public health measures has given the virus more time to spread, and companies, not just politicians, have historically underestimated the economic damage that the virus can cause. The exchequer’s plan is also not without issues: The Economist noted that the furloughed workers, unable to work under the current proposal, would deflate labor supply towards those industries that are seeing an increase in demand; this in turn would prevent the labor market from operating at maximum efficiency (attached link).

The unemployment rate that was recorded by the UK Office of National Statistics for the period of November-January was 3.9%. As reported by the Financial Times, the UK has already seen a loss of 200,000 jobs in the leisure and hospitality sectors as a direct result of COVID-19. The Financial Times predicts that by the end of the second quarter, that number will rise to approximately 700,000 across all industries. As of March 26, around 9,500 residents have tested positive for the disease and the government has continued to restrict gatherings and push social distancing and self-quarantine. Due to this, the unemployment rate will be likely to double by the end of the March-May period.
